<ns2987:section xmlns:ns2987="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.j2se.accessControl.applicationAccessControl">
    
    <ns2988:title xmlns:ns2988="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Application Access Control</ns2988:title>

<ns2989:para xmlns:ns2989="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">In Java 2 one can apply the same security restrictions to applications as
to applets by running the application under a security manager. </ns2989:para>
<ns2990:para xmlns:ns2990="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
<ns2991:programlisting xmlns:ns2991="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
java -Djava.security.manager MyApplication
</ns2991:programlisting>
</ns2990:para>
<ns2992:para xmlns:ns2992="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">If no further permissions are granted via a policy file, the application will
run in the Sandbox model, <ns2993:abbrev xmlns:ns2993="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">i.e.</ns2993:abbrev> the application cannot access any system 
resources except the very basic ones like operating system and java version 
information and file separator characters</ns2992:para>.

<ns2994:para xmlns:ns2994="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Typically the access permissions are specified in a policy file where one
can specify the permissions either at a very course or at a very fine level.</ns2994:para>
    
